Kazuo,

The 1D flame models solve low-Mach-number equations that assume 
constant pressure.

For the zero-D reactor objects, the situation is very different.  
Reactors have a specified volume, not pressure, but deformable walls 
(or free pistons) may be installed on reactors in such a way that the 
pressure stays very close to a constant.  See the &quot;reactors.pdf&quot; 
document from last summer&#39;s Cantera Workshop (available at the 
sourceforge site) for more information.



